main event: Four circular objects, approximately 30-50 feet in diameter, were sighted by two USAF pilots in the Pacific Ocean on September 9, 1963.
interesting points: The objects were observed moving at a speed of 200-300 knots and an altitude of approximately 25,000 feet.
The objects remained steady, with no change in speed or direction, and disappeared after 3 minutes of observation.
No sound or exhaust was observed from the objects.
The sighting occurred near the handle of the Big Dipper constellation.
The report concludes that the objects were likely natural phenomena, a familiar aircraft, an astronomical object, or a satellite, due to insufficient data for a definitive evaluation.
